Practice Project: Insurance Cost Analysis¶

Goal: Predict individual medical insurance charges using demographic and lifestyle data.

📘 Overview¶

This project explores how factors like age, BMI, and smoking status affect medical costs.
A Polynomial Ridge Regression model was trained and evaluated to estimate insurance charges.

💡 Insights¶

  • Smoking status is the dominant cost driver.
  • Age has moderate impact; BMI contributes less strongly.
  • Ensemble or segmented models could further improve predictions for extreme charges.

In this project, I performed analytics operations on an insurance database that uses the below mentioned parameters.

Parameter Description Content type
age Age in years integer
gender Male or Female integer (1 or 2)
bmi Body mass index float
no_of_children Number of children integer
smoker Whether smoker or not integer (0 or 1)
region Which US region - NW, NE, SW, SE integer (1,2,3 or 4 respectively)
charges Annual Insurance charges in USD float

🎯 Project Objectives¶

This project focuses on understanding and predicting medical insurance costs using regression techniques.
Beyond modeling, it emphasizes feature relationships, interpretability, and performance evaluation.

In this project, I:¶

  • Loaded and prepared the dataset using pandas, ensuring all missing and inconsistent values were handled systematically.
  • Performed exploratory data analysis (EDA) to uncover key cost drivers such as age, BMI, and smoking status.
  • Visualized relationships between numeric and categorical features using correlation heatmaps, boxplots, and regression plots.
  • Built and compared regression models, starting with:
    • Simple Linear Regression for single-variable relationships.
    • Multiple Linear Regression using all available features.
  • Refined model performance through Ridge Regression and Polynomial Features to capture non-linear effects and reduce overfitting.
  • Evaluated models using metrics such as R², MAE, and RMSE to assess accuracy and reliability.
  • Derived actionable insights, identifying smoking and age as the strongest predictors of higher insurance charges.

Handle missing data:

  • For continuous attributes (e.g., age), I replaced missing values with the mean.
  • For categorical attributes (e.g., smoker), replaced missing values with the most frequent value.
  • Updated the data types of the respective columns.
  • Verified the update using df.info().
In [15]:
# Identify the most frequent 'smoker' value
is_smoker = df['smoker'].value_counts().idxmax()

# Replace NaN values in 'smoker' column safely
df = df.assign(smoker=df['smoker'].fillna(is_smoker))

# Calculate mean age (converted to float first)
mean_age = df['age'].astype(float).mean()

# Replace NaN values in 'age' column safely
df = df.assign(age=df['age'].fillna(mean_age))

# Convert columns to integer type as needed
df[['age', 'smoker']] = df[['age', 'smoker']].astype(int)

Created a training pipeline that uses StandardScaler(), PolynomialFeatures() and LinearRegression() to create a model that can predict the charges value using all the other attributes of the dataset. There should be even further improvement in the performance.

In [24]:
Input=[('scale',StandardScaler()), ('polynomial', PolynomialFeatures(include_bias=False)), ('model', LinearRegression())]
pipe=Pipeline(Input)
Z = Z.astype(float)
pipe.fit(Z,Y)
ypipe=pipe.predict(Z)
print(r2_score(Y,ypipe))

0.8452576213500093

A good R^2 value is produced, now we must test how well the model generalizes on unseen data or we risk overfitting.

Step 5 : Model Refinement¶

“This step uses polynomial features and ridge regularization to capture non-linear relationships while controlling overfitting.”

Splitted the data into training and testing subsets, assuming that 20% of the data will be reserved for testing. We are testing how well the model generalizes on unseen data. This prevents overfitting -- when a model memorizes data instead of learning patterns.

In [25]:
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(Z, Y, test_size=0.2, random_state=1)

Initialized a Ridge regressor that used hyperparameter $ \alpha = 0.1 $. Fit the model using training data data subset. Print the $ R^2 $ score for the testing data.

This reduces overfitting by shrinking large coefficients that might over react to the noise in the data.

In [26]:
RidgeModel=Ridge(alpha=0.1)
RidgeModel.fit(x_train, y_train)
yhat = RidgeModel.predict(x_test)
print(r2_score(y_test,yhat))

0.6760807731582404

R^2 of 0.676 means the model explains about 67.8% of the variance in insurance charges, capturing most of the trend but not all.

To further dial in we applied polynomial transformation to the training parameters with degree=2. Used this transformed feature set to fit the same regression model, as above, using the training subset. Printed the $ R^2 $ score for the testing subset.

In [27]:
pr = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2)
x_train_pr = pr.fit_transform(x_train)
x_test_pr = pr.fit_transform(x_test)
RidgeModel.fit(x_train_pr, y_train)
y_hat = RidgeModel.predict(x_test_pr)
print(r2_score(y_test,y_hat))

0.7835631107608146

Interpretation¶

Because insurance costs are not purely linear (e.g. the impact of BMI might increase exponentially beyond certain thresholds). Polynomial terms allow the model to capture nonlinear relatioinships that simple linear models cannot.

The R^2 score increased from .676 to 0.784, meaning the model now explains 78.4% of the variance.

Interpretation¶

Model Fit and Residual Patterns¶

The model captures the overall trend between actual and predicted medical charges (R² = 0.78),
but it exhibits systematic bias:

  • Overpredicts costs for low-charge patients.
  • Underpredicts costs for high-charge patients.
  • Residual variance increases with charge level, indicating heteroskedasticity.

Together, the predicted vs. actual and residual plots confirm that the model performs well overall but struggles with extreme cost values.

Interpretation:¶

The model distinguishes smokers and non-smokers effectively, as shown by the clear cost separation. However, residuals reveal that predictions for smokers show higher variance and slight overprediction bias. This suggests potential benefits from modeling interaction effects or log-transforming charges to stabilize variance.

Model Evaluation and Insights¶

While the model fits the majority of the data reasonably well, the residual plot reveals a systematic bias:

  • It overpredicts costs for low-charge patients (many residuals below zero at low predicted values).
  • It underpredicts costs for high-charge patients (residuals above zero at high predicted values).
  • The widening spread of residuals suggests heteroskedasticity — prediction errors grow for more expensive cases, which is common in healthcare cost modeling.

In other words, the model captures general cost trends but struggles with extreme cases on both ends.

    'MAE': [

    ],
    'RMSE': [
        np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_lr)),
        np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_ridge))
    ]
}

Model Comparison Summary¶

We evaluated both regression models on their ability to predict insurance charges.

The Polynomial Ridge Regression model achieved the best overall performance:

  • R²: 0.784 → Explains ~78% of variance in medical charges
  • MAE: ≈ $3.9K → On average, predictions are within $3,900 of actual costs
  • RMSE: ≈ $5.7K → Large prediction errors are typically within $5,700

The Polynomial Ridge model explained ~78% of the variance in charges (R² ≈ 0.78). Average error was MAE ≈ $3.9K with RMSE ≈ $5.7K. Plots show solid fit on typical cases but systematic patterns at the extremes: the model overpredicts low-cost cases and underpredicts high-cost outliers, with error variance increasing with predicted charges (heteroskedasticity). Next steps: log-transforming charges, adding interaction terms (e.g., smoker × BMI), or moving to tree-based ensembles for extreme-case calibration. The model is suitable for the general population; high-risk segments merit specialized models.

Model Applicability in Real-World Scenarios¶

The polynomial ridge regression model performs well for the majority of patients, capturing around 78% of variance in medical charges. It reliably predicts typical costs based on age, BMI, and smoking status, making it useful for portfolio-level trend analysis and pricing decisions.

However, for high-cost patients (outliers), the model tends to underpredict their true charges and exhibits higher variance.
In real-world insurance modeling, these cases would typically be handled separately—either through specialized high-cost claim models or ensemble techniques that combine linear and nonlinear approaches.
The current model would therefore be deployed for the general population, while high-risk, high-cost segments would require more complex, event-driven predictive modeling.
